MissionCommands.Message: We are about an hour away from the planned ignition time and the powered descent.
Moon, here we come. Lets plant those legs on the surface.

Roger! The tasks ahead is to set up for the burn using P63, then get into attitude. P63 will guide us along the trajectory, and P64 will get us towards the final approach. During final approach, P66 will then take over for the landing itself.
Switching FDAI 1 mode to INRTL.
[Request PDI ignition time by pressing REQUEST PDI on the COMM menu. Take a note of the ignition time.]
Roger. Let's set up attitude control modes. On the LGC, key V49E.
Let us maneuver to the ignition attitude. Use V22E to change R2 to +11000. Leave the other two at +00000.
Switching ATTITUDE CONTROL to MODE CONT.
The attitude is now in the hands of the PGNS.
Completing the auto maneuvering routine. [Press ROGER when complete.]
Maneuver complete.
Roger. [Key V48E to reconfigure the DAP, then Key V21E to change R1. Following the DAP Setup checklist, set R1 to +22102 and press ENTER. Hit PRO until the routine is complete.]
Use Timescale to T -25 minutes to ignition.
Let's get set up for the burn! Key V37E63E.
Ensure the EVENT TIMER is stopped then set the EVENT TIMER to 54:00, counting up.
Timescale to about T minus 8 minutes to burn. We will start the EVENT TIMER when it's exactly 6 minutes left to ignition.
Verify the attitude. If the PGNS don't align well with the intended attitude, take manual control and correct it, then return to auto.
At exactly T minus 6 minutes, start the EVENT TIMER!
Key PRO to proceed in P63 to advance. V50N18 is asking for PGNS attitude control. Press PRO again to accept this.
Let's be prepared to take over control if needed during the descent, we want to land this thing today.
Roger. Press PRO on the LGC when satisfied with the attitude. The DSKY displays V06N62.
The most important piece of data is in R2, the time to ignition. R1 shows the absolute value of your velocity and R3 shows the accumulated delta V.
T minus 2 minutes to ignition, set MASTER ARM to ON.
At T minus 35 seconds, the DSKY’s gonna go blank for about 5 seconds. When we hit T minus 30, flip the ENG ARM switch on Panel 1 to DES—that’ll arm the descent engine.
Okay, let’s flip the PRLNT QTY MON switch on Panel 1 to DES 1. That’ll bring up the fuel quantity on the digital readouts up top on Panel 1, so we can keep an eye on it.
At T minus 5 seconds, V99 will show, asking you for permission to ignite the ENGINE. Press PRO once and wait for ignition.
Ignition!
Switching rate and altitude source to PGNS.
Open the P63 descent cue card from the MISSION PAD and the POWERED DESCENT CHECKLIST.
DES ENG CMD OVRD to ON.
Roger, monitor the altitude and rates.
Roger. Waiting for 40k ft altitude and VEL + ALT light out.
Please verify, our data indicate switch to landing radar data.
Roger, permitting landing radar data. [Key V57E on the LGC]
Program Alarm!
Check the alarm code by keying V05 N09.
1202, are we go on that?
We are checking.
We are go on the 1202.
Roger, proceeding with the descent.

If the LGC triggers an error, the Master Alarm will trigger on some of them. You can mute it by pressing it, and press RSET on the DSKY to clear it, or view the error using V05 N09. This will also clear it.
Waiting for P64 to start. Monitor the descent.
Ok, P64 has started and the pitch-over should happen. Key V77E to prepare the attitude hold mode for P66.
Roger.
Correct the landing location if needed.
Use the P64 cue card located in the same checklist, and pay attention to the LPD.
Program alarm!
P66 will automatically start when P64 is satisfied.
P66! Setting controls to ATT HOLD. Get a stable control of the attitude, then maneuver us down to a safe landing area.
Use the ROD control for a steady descent, monitor the data.
When you find a suitable spot, tilt the spacecraft so your velocities on the X-Pointer is nulled, and slowly bring the spacecraft down for a soft landing.
Pay attention to the fuel, and focus on the landing.
Contact! Shut off the DPS ENGINE immediately!
Now, Key V37E68E to start Program 68. Excellent job!
The Lunar Module has landed.
Great work! A decade of work coming together, piece by piece. Sure feels like a long time ago since you ascended into space in that Mercury rocket, doesn't it?
Sure does. This was great, thanks all for making this possible.

Roger, good job. Let's configure this craft into a Lunar Stay operations mode. Complete the "EPS Check, Post-Lunar-Landing" checklist located in the Lunar Stay section of the Mission Pad. Press ROGER when complete.
Then complete the "Lunar Stay Subsystems Check" checklist to reconfigure the craft, shutting down systems not needed while standing still on the lunar surface. Press ROGER when complete.
Checklist complete, we are ready for lunar stay operations.
Roger! Once again, good job, let's get out on the surface, shall we?
Roger, let's prepare for EGRESS and EVA.
Roger, run the "Subsystem Configuration for EVA Preparation" checklist, this will start the EVA period of this mission. Press ROGER when complete.
Checklist complete.
Roger, then let's put on the EVA suits. Use the C-Menu->CREW MEMBERS->MANAGE CREW and activate the EVA suit on the CDR and the LMP. Press ROGER when ready.
Then complete the "Final Subsystems Configuration for Egress" checklist to verify cockpit configurations. Press ROGER when ready.
We are now ready for cabin depressurization and EVA.
Roger, please proceed with Cabin Depressurization.
Ok, move down to the forward hatch and set the Cabin Relief and Vent Valve to OPEN, and monitor the cabin pressure. When it is zero, open the hatch.
Roger, let's get out to the Lunar Module.
It's a small step for man, a giant leap for mankind.
Beautiful. How does it look?
It looks gray, silent, and there seems to be a lot of lunar dust and rocks. I will keep walking and gather a lunar rock sample (not yet available in Reentry).
Roger. Take your time, and return to the cockpit when you are ready.
I will return back inside now.
Roger, use the circular button to return back inside.
Welcome back!
Thank you, that was fun. Let's return this cabin back to a pressurized lunar stay configuration.
Roger, run the "Post-EVA Final Subsystems Configuration" checklist and press ROGER when complete.
Then remove the EVA suit using the MANAGE CREW menu.
Good work out there, we really made it. In the next mission, we will perform the lunar ascent, and rendezvous the CSM in orbit.
Yes, we did well, we have landed on the Moon. I'm pretty sure Patrick would have been proud of our firsts today!
This completes the mission.

Title: THE LANDING
Description: With the LM activated, the Powered Descent Initiation maneuver must be prepared. The Lunar Guidance System will be used to automatically maneuver the spacecraft down to the surface, followed by a semi-automatic landing.
BriefingText:
Flight Plan
- Powered Descent and Lunar Landing
- Lunar Stay
- Ascent & Rendezvous
- Trans-Earth Injection
- Entry and Landing

The CSM as made the circular orbit burn, and is orbiting the moon at an altitude of 60 nmi.
The Lunar Module is activated and is in the descent orbit. It needs to be prepared for the powered descent, before igniting the descent engine and landing on the Moon.

After landing, the Lunar Module must be reconfigured for Lunar Stay operations. We will then perform an EVA and walk on the Moon.
